    Total vertices: |V‚āĀ‚ą™V‚āā‚ą™V‚āÉ| = 3+3+3 - 1-1-1 = 6.

STEP 3a: Pattern (a) ‚ÄĒ THE (b,d) TRAP
--------------------------------------------------

  Given: v‚Üía‚Üíb‚Üív and v‚Üíc‚Üíd‚Üív in tournament T.
  v beats a,c and b,d beat v.

  CLAIM: The arc between b and d creates an extra 3-cycle.

  For NO extra cycle through v:
    Need d‚Üía (otherwise v‚Üía‚Üí...‚Üíd‚Üív has shortcut through d)
    Need b‚Üíc (otherwise v‚Üíc‚Üí...‚Üíb‚Üív has shortcut through b)

  Actually, more precisely:
    0-cycle v‚Üía‚Üíd‚Üív requires a‚Üíd: avoid by d‚Üía ‚úď
    0-cycle v‚Üíc‚Üíb‚Üív requires c‚Üíb: avoid by b‚Üíc ‚úď

  Now arc (b,d) is TRAPPED:
    If d‚Üíb: b‚Üíc (forced) + c‚Üíd (from C‚āā) + d‚Üíb ‚üĻ cycle {b,c,d}
    If b‚Üíd: d‚Üía (forced) + a‚Üíb (from C‚āĀ) + b‚Üíd ‚üĻ cycle {a,b,d}

  EITHER WAY: an extra 3-cycle exists. dc3 > 3. őĪ‚āĀ > 3. ‚úó

  NOTE: This argument requires d‚Üía and b‚Üíc.
  What if we DON'T force d‚Üía? Then a‚Üíd, and v‚Üía‚Üíd‚Üív is a cycle.
  But that's an EXTRA cycle through v. dc3 > 3. őĪ‚āĀ > 3. ‚úó
  Similarly for b‚Üíc.

  ‚ąī Pattern (a) always forces őĪ‚āĀ > 3. ‚úď

  VERIFICATION at n=7:
    Total tournaments with 3 fixed cycles through v=0: 32768
    Of these with dc3=3 exactly: 0
    CONFIRMED: dc3 > 3 in ALL cases. ‚úď

STEP 3b: Pattern (b) ‚ÄĒ No common vertex
--------------------------------------------------

  V‚āĀ={a,x,z}, V‚āā={a,b,y}, V‚āÉ={b,z,w}
  (or any configuration with 6 vertices, pairwise 1-vertex intersection)

  Minimum n = 6 (all 6 vertices needed).

